<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-639-178  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 639 178.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  June 20 1990 n135 p151(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Beating the system. (Read Only)</TITLE><AUTHOR>John, William.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BooksReview.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Beating the SystemandM;One of the most mysterious concepts in our culture today is that of computerhacking.andP;  What is it?andP;  Why and how do people do it?andP;  Where does it fit intoour code of ethics?andP;  Indeed, is it necessarily wrong?andM;In their book Beating the System, authors Owen Bowcott and Sally Hamiltonattempt to answer some of these questions using the case of Edward AustinSingh as their base.andM;Singh was arrested in 1988 at the University of Surrey where, posing as astudent, he had gained access to the university's computer network andthrough it penetrated confidential data on networks as far away as the US,Germany and Switzerland, including a supposedly secure US militaryinstallation.andP;  He was questioned but never prosecuted, although he facedcharges of burglary, spying, extortion and contravening the Official SecretsAct.andM;Currently, attitudes to hacking can appear ambivalent.andP;  Hackers have alwayshad a slightly romantic image and many claim to be champions of freedom ofinformation.andP;  Tiger teams of hackers are employed by big corporations to hacklegally into systems to try to find loopholes in the system security.andP;  On theother hand, they can wreck valuable work -- witness the recent hacker whodeleted vital medical records from a London University system.andM;As a history of hacking to date, Beating the System is fascinating and wellwritten, but it suffers from almost immediate obsolescence.andP;  Hackers arebeing uncovered all the time, and while legislation has been slow, it ishappening.andP;  And the publisher's note on the flyleaf that hacking will beillegal by summer 1990, while quite possibly true, does nothing to enhancethe book's shelf life.andO;</TEXT></DOC>